rites its laws.\224 The meaning is that the poet translates more clearly the ) Tj0 -11.52  TD -0.0929  Tc -0.0271  Tw (character of his people than the lawgiver does. In Moses\222) Tj225.12 0  TD -0.0823  Tc -0.0377  Tw ( case the two were combined in one person. ) Tj174.72 0  TD 0  Tc -0.12  Tw ( ) Tj-363.84 -11.52  TD /F2 10.08  Tf0.0261  Tc 0.8139  Tw (Adam Clarke\222s Commentary) Tj117.6 0  TD /F0 10.08  Tf-0.0682  Tc 0.6682  Tw ( writes about this chapter: \223On the inimitable excellence of this ode much has ) Tj-153.6 -11.52  TD -0.0879  Tc 0.3973  Tw (been written by commentators, critics, and poets, and it is allowed by the best judges to contain a specimen ) Tj432.48 0  TD 0.03  Tc -0.15  Tw (of almost ) Tj-432.48 -11.52  TD -0.0814  Tc 0.6941  Tw (every species of excellence in composition. It is so thoroughly poetic that even the dull Jews themselves found they ) Tj0 -11.52  TD -0.0899  Tc 0.7335  Tw (could not write it in the prose form; and hence, it is distinguished as poetry in every Hebrew Bible by being written ) TjT* -0.0207  Tc 0.2207  Tw (in its own ) Tj43.2 0  TD -0.0805  Tc 0.2965  Tw (hemistichs or short half lines, which is the general form of the Hebrew poetry; and were it translated in the ) Tj-43.2 -11.52  TD -0.0841  Tc 0.9241  Tw (same way it would be more easily understood. The song itself has suffered both by transcribers and translators, the ) Tj0 -11.52  TD -0.0854  Tc 0.9254  Tw (former having mistaken some le) Tj131.04 0  TD -0.0758  Tc 0.7558  Tw (tters in different places, and made wrong combinations of them in others. As to the ) Tj-131.04 -11.52  TD -0.0624  Tc 1.7361  Tw (translators, most of them have followed their own fancy, from good Mr. Ainsworth, who ruined it by the most ) Tj0 -11.04  TD -0.0865  Tc -0.0335  Tw (inanimate rhyming version, to certain latter poets, who have cas) Tj252 0  TD -0.0432  Tc -0.0768  Tw (t it unhallowedly into a European mold.\224 ) Tj165.12 0  TD 0  Tc -0.12  Tw ( ) Tj-38